# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: software-supply-chain-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Code signing can provide several valuable features.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] The most common use of code signing is to provide security when deploying; in some programming languages, it can also be used to help prevent namespace conflicts.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Almost every code signing implementation will provide some sort of digital signature mechanism to verify the identity of the author or build system, and a checksum to verify that the object has not been modified.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] It can also be used to provide versioning information about an object or to store other metadata about an object.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] The efficacy of code signing as an authentication mechanism for software depends on the security of underpinning signing keys.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] As with other public key infrastructure (PKI) technologies, the integrity of the system relies on publishers securing their private keys against unauthorized access.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Keys stored in software on general-purpose computers are susceptible to compromise.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Therefore, it is more secure, and best practice, to store keys in secure, tamper-proof, cryptographic hardware devices known as hardware security modules or HSMs.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Many code signing implementations will provide a way to sign the code using a system involving a pair of keys, one public and one private, similar to the process employed by TLS or SSH.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] For example, in the case of .NET, the developer uses a private key to sign their libraries or executables each time they build.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] This key will be unique to a developer or group or sometimes per application or object.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] The developer can either generate this key on their own or obtain one from a trusted certificate authority (CA).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Code signing is particularly valuable in distributed environments, where the source of a given piece of code may not be immediately evident - for example Java applets, ActiveX controls and other active web and browser scripting code.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Another important usage is to safely provide updates and patches to existing software.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Windows, Mac OS X, and most Linux distributions provide updates using code signing to ensure that it is not possible for others to maliciously distribute code via the patch system.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] It allows the receiving operating system to verify that the update is legitimate, even if the update was delivered by third parties or physical media (disks).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Code signing is used on Windows and Mac OS X to authenticate software on first run, ensuring that the software has not been maliciously tampered with by a third-party distributor or download site.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Debian-based Linux distributions (among others) validate downloaded packages using public key cryptography.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] The public key used to authenticate the code signature should be traceable back to a trusted root authority CA, preferably using a secure public key infrastructure (PKI).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] This does not ensure that the code itself can be trusted, only that it comes from the stated source (or more explicitly, from a particular private key).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] A CA provides a root trust level and is able to assign trust to others by proxy.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] If a user trusts a CA, then the user can presumably trust the legitimacy of code that is signed with a key generated by that CA or one of its proxies.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Many operating systems and frameworks contain built-in trust for one or more certification authorities.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] It is also commonplace for large organizations to implement a private CA, internal to the organization, which provides the same features as public CAs, but it is only trusted within the organization.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Extended validation (EV) code signing certificates are subject to additional validation and technical requirements.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] These guidelines are based on the CA/B Forum's Baseline Requirements and Extended Validation Guidelines.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Certain applications, such as signing Windows 10 kernel-mode drivers, require an EV code signing certificate.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] This is an example of a decoded EV code signing certificate used by SSL.com to sign software.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] `SSL.com EV Code Signing Intermediate CA RSA R3` is shown as the Issuer's commonName, identifying this as an EV code signing certificate.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] The certificate's `Subject` field describes SSL Corp as an organization.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] `Code Signing` is shown as the sole X509v3 Extended Key Usage.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] The other model is the trust on first use model, in which developers can choose to provide their own self-generated key.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] In this scenario, the user would normally have to obtain the public key in some fashion directly from the developer to verify the object is from them for the first time.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Many code signing systems will store the public key inside the signature.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Some software frameworks and OSs that check the code's signature before executing will allow you to choose to trust that developer from that point on after the first run.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] An application developer can provide a similar system by including the public keys with the installer.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] The key can then be used to ensure that any subsequent objects that need to run, such as upgrades, plugins, or another application, are all verified as coming from that same developer.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Time-stamping was designed to circumvent the trust warning that will appear in the case of an expired certificate.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] In effect, time-stamping extends the code trust beyond the validity period of a certificate.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] In the event that a certificate has to be revoked due to a compromise, a specific date and time of the compromising event will become part of the revocation record.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] In this case, time-stamping helps establish whether the code was signed before or after the certificate was compromised.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Developers need to sign their iOS and tvOS apps before running them on any real device and before uploading them to the App Store.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] This is needed to prove that the developer owns a valid Apple Developer ID.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] An application needs a valid profile or certificate so that it can run on the devices.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Like any security measure, code signing can be defeated.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Users can be tricked into running unsigned code, or even into running code that refuses to validate, and the system only remains secure as long as the private key remains private.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] It is also important to note that code signing does not protect the end user from any malicious activity or unintentional software bugs by the software author — it merely ensures that the software has not been modified by anyone other than the author.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Sometimes, sandbox systems do not accept certificates, because of a false time-stamp or because of an excess usage of RAM.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Microsoft implements a form of code signing (based on Authenticode) provided for Microsoft tested drivers.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Since drivers run in the kernel, they can destabilize the system or open the system to security holes.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] For this reason, Microsoft tests drivers submitted to its WHQL program.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] After the driver has passed, Microsoft signs that version of the driver as being safe.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] On 32-bit systems only, installing drivers that are not validated with Microsoft is possible after agreeing to allow the installation at a prompt warning the user that the code is unsigned.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] For .NET (managed) code, there is an additional mechanism called Strong Name Signing that uses Public/Private keys and SHA-1 hash as opposed to certificates.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] However, Microsoft discourages reliance on Strong Name Signing as a replacement for Authenticode.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] The CAs subsequently issued announcements on compliance with the decision.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] In the context of consumer devices such as games consoles, the term "unsigned code" is often used to refer to an application which has not been signed with the cryptographic key normally required for software to be accepted and executed.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] Most console games have to be signed with a secret key designed by the console maker or the game will not load on the console (both to enforce Vendor lock-in and combat software piracy).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] There are several methods to get unsigned code to execute which include software exploits, the use of a modchip, a technique known as the swap trick or running a softmod.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] It may not initially seem obvious why simply copying a signed application onto another DVD does not allow it to boot.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] On the Xbox, the reason for this is that the Xbox executable file (XBE) contains a media-type flag, which specifies the type of media that the XBE is bootable from.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] On nearly all Xbox software, this is set such that the executable will only boot from factory-produced discs, so simply copying the executable to burnable media is enough to stop the execution of the software.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/code-signing] However, since the executable is signed, simply changing the value of the flag is not possible as this alters the signature of the executable, causing it to fail validation when checked.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/devsecops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] Reproducible builds can act as part of a chain of trust; the source code can be signed, and deterministic compilation can prove that the binary was compiled from trusted source code.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] Verified reproducible builds provide a strong countermeasure against attacks where binaries do not match their source code, e.g., because an attacker has inserted malicious code into a binary.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] This is a relevant attack; attackers sometimes attack binaries but not the source code, e.g., because they can only change the distributed binary or to evade detection since it is the source code that developers normally review and modify.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] In a survey of 17 experts, reproducible builds had a very high utility rating from 58.8% participants, but also a high-cost rating from 70.6%.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] Various efforts are being made to modify software development tools to reduce these costs.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] For the compilation process to be deterministic, the input to the compiler must be the same, regardless of the build environment used.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] This typically involves normalizing variables that may change, such as order of input files, timestamps, locales, and paths.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] Additionally, the compilers must not introduce non-determinism themselves.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] This sometimes happens when using hash tables with a random hash seed value.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] It can also happen when using the address of variables because that varies from address space layout randomization (ASLR).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] Build systems, such as Bazel, GNU Guix, and Gitian, can be used to automate deterministic build processes.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] The GNU Project used reproducible builds in the early 1990s.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] Changelogs from 1992 indicate the ongoing effort.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] One of the older projects to promote reproducible builds is the Bitcoin project with Gitian, and later, GNU Guix.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] In 2013, the Tor (anonymity network) project started using Gitian for their reproducible builds.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] Starting in 2011, a reproducible Java build system was developed for the decentralized peer-to-peer FOSS project DirectDemocracyP2P.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] The concepts of the system's application to automated updates recommendation support was first presented in April 2013 at Decentralized Coordination.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] A treatise focusing on the implementation details of the reproducible Java compilation tool itself was published in 2015.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] In July 2013, the Debian project started implementing reproducible builds across its entire package archive.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] By July 2017, more than 90% of the packages in the repository were proven to build reproducibly.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] In November 2018, the Reproducible Builds project joined the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] F-Droid uses reproducible builds to provide a guarantee that distributed APKs use the claimed free source code.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] The Tails portable operating system uses reproducible builds and explains to others how to verify their distribution.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] NixOS claims 100% build reproducibility as of June 2021 for their minimal ISO releases.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] As of May 2020, Arch Linux is working on making all official packages reproducible.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] As of March 2025, Debian live images for Bookworm are reproducible.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] The FreeBSD operating system builds reproducibly and without root access since October 2025.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] According to the Reproducible Builds project, timestamps are "the biggest source of reproducibility issues.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] In some cases other changes must be made to make a build process reproducible.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] For example, some data structures do not guarantee a stable order in each execution.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/reproducible-builds] A typical solution is to modify the build process to specify a sorted output from those structures.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] A **software supply chain** is the components, libraries, tools, and processes used to develop, build, and publish a software artifact.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] A **software bill of materials** (**SBOM**) declares the inventory of components used to build a software artifact, including any open source and proprietary software components.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] It is the software analogue to the traditional manufacturing BOM, which is used as part of supply chain management.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] SBOMs are a strategy for improving transparency in the software supply chain.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] Software supply chain attacks compromise an upstream component — such as a widely-used library, a build tool, or a distribution channel — in order to simultaneously affect all downstream users of that component.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] High-profile incidents such as the SolarWinds attack illustrated the scale and reach of such attacks.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] Researchers have catalogued the attack surface into a taxonomy covering all stages from source-code contribution to package distribution, linking attack vectors to real-world incidents and corresponding safeguards.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] Another important concept in software supply chains is provenance: signed attestations can record where a software artifact came from, which source and dependencies were used, and which steps in the build pipeline produced it.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] Provenance frameworks such as in-toto help downstream users verify that a release was built by an expected process and help detect tampering between source retrieval, build, and distribution.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] An SBOM allows builders to make sure open-source and third-party software components are up to date and respond quickly to new vulnerabilities.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] Buyers and other stakeholders can use an SBOM to perform vulnerability or license analysis, which can be used to evaluate and manage risk in a product.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] While many companies use a spreadsheet for general BOM management, there are additional risks and issues in an SBOM written to a spreadsheet, such as the inability to automatically enrich it with vulnerability data or integrate it into security toolchains.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] It is best practice for SBOMs to be collectively stored in a repository that can be part of other automation systems and easily queried by other applications.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] Cybersecurity transparency studies, including TRACS 2025, identify the availability of SBOMs as one of the criteria used when purchasing information security solutions.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] However, not all enterprise security products provide publicly available SBOMs.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] Research on open-source ecosystems indicates that policy-driven SBOMs remain rare in practice: one large-scale study found that only about 0.56% of popular GitHub repositories contain SBOMs created in accordance with formal security or compliance policies.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] Also, according to other research, fewer than half of tested software projects include SBOMs in their releases, and many of those SBOMs are incomplete or do not fully conform to established standards.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] At the same time, corporate-level surveys report that approximately 60–76 % of enterprises require SBOMs from suppliers or have integrated SBOMs into procurement and supply-chain risk management processes.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] US President Joe Biden’s **Executive Order 14028 on Improving the Nation’s Cybersecurity** of May 12, 2021 ordered NIST and NTIA to lay down guidelines for software supply chain management, including for SBOMs.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/software-supply-chain] The "automation support" requirement specifies the need for "automatic generation," which is possible with the use of Software Composition Analysis (SCA) solutions.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] A **supply chain attack** is a cyber-attack that seeks to damage an organization by targeting less secure elements in the supply chain.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain attack can occur in any industry, from the financial sector, oil industry, to a government sector.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain attack can happen in software or hardware.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Cybercriminals typically tamper with the manufacturing or distribution of a product by installing malware or hardware-based spying components.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Symantec's 2019 Internet Security Threat Report states that supply chain attacks increased by 78 percent in 2018.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain is a system of activities involved in handling, distributing, manufacturing, and processing goods in order to move resources from a vendor into the hands of the final consumer.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] A supply chain is a complex network of interconnected players governed by supply and demand.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Alternatively, the term can be used to describe attacks exploiting the software supply chain, in which an apparently low-level or unimportant software component used by other software can be used to inject malicious code into the larger software that depends on the component.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In a more general sense, a supply chain attack may not necessarily involve electronics.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In 2010 when burglars gained access to the pharmaceutical giant Eli Lilly's supply warehouse, by drilling a hole in the roof and loading $80 million worth of prescription drugs into a truck, they could also have been said to carry out a supply chain attack.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] However, this article will discuss cyber attacks on physical supply networks that rely on technology; hence, a supply chain attack is a method used by cyber-criminals.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Generally, supply chain attacks on information systems begin with an advanced persistent threat (APT) that determines a member of the supply network with the weakest cyber security in order to affect the target organization.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Hackers don't usually directly target a larger entity, such as the United States Government, but instead target the entity's software.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The third-party software is often less protected, leading to an easier target.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] According to an investigation produced by Verizon Enterprise, 92% of the cyber security incidents analyzed in their survey occurred among small firms.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain networks are considered to be particularly vulnerable due to their multiple interconnected components.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] APTs can often gain access to sensitive information by physically tampering with the production of the product.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Poorly managed supply chain management systems can become significant hazards for cyber attacks, which can lead to a loss of sensitive customer information, disruption of the manufacturing process, and could damage a company's reputation.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Wired reported a connecting thread in recent software supply chain attacks, as of 3 May 2019.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] These have been surmised to have spread from infected, pirated, popular compilers posted on pirate websites.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] That is, corrupted versions of Apple's Xcode and Microsoft Visual Studio.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] At the end of 2013, Target, a US retailer, was hit by one of the largest data breaches in the history of the retail industry.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Between 27 November and 15 December 2013, Target's American brick-and-mortar stores experienced a data hack.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Around 40 million customers' credit and debit cards became susceptible to fraud after malware was introduced into the POS system in over 1,800 stores.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The data breach of Target's customer information saw a direct impact on the company's profit, which fell 46 percent in the fourth quarter of 2013.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Six months prior the company began installing a $1.6 million cyber security system.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Target had a team of security specialists to monitor its computers constantly.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Nonetheless, the supply chain attack circumvented these security measures.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] It is believed that cyber criminals infiltrated a third party supplier to gain access to Target's main data network.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Although not officially confirmed, investigation officials suspect that the hackers first broke into Target's network on 15 November 2013 using passcode credentials stolen from Fazio Mechanical Services, a Pennsylvania-based provider of HVAC systems.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Ninety lawsuits have been filed against Target by customers for carelessness and compensatory damages.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Target spent around $61 million responding to the breach, according to its fourth-quarter report to investors.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet is a computer worm that is widely believed to be a joint U.S.-Israeli cyber operation, though neither government has officially confirmed involvement.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The worm specifically targets industrial control systems, particularly those that automate electromechanical processes, such as factory machinery and nuclear enrichment equipment.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet was designed to manipulate programmable logic controllers (PLCs), disrupting industrial equipment by issuing unauthorized commands while simultaneously feeding falsified operations data to monitoring systems to conceal its activity.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet is widely believed to have been developed to disrupt Iran's enriched uranium programs.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Kevin Hogan, Senior Director of Security Response at Symantec, stated that most infections occurred in Iran.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Analysts suggest that its primary target was the Natanz uranium enrichment facility.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Stuxnet was initially introduced into Iran's Natanz facility via infected USB flash drives, requiring physical access to the target network.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] According to reports, engineers or maintenance workers, either knowingly or unknowingly, facilitated its entry into the plant.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Once inside, the worm spread autonomously, exploiting multiple zero-day vulnerabilities in Windows systems to propagate across networked machines running Siemens industrial control software.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In recent years malware known as Suceful, Plotus, Tyupkin and GreenDispenser have affected automated teller machines globally, especially in Russia and Ukraine.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] GreenDispenser specifically gives attackers the ability to walk up to an infected ATM system and remove its cash vault.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] When installed, GreenDispenser may display an 'out of service' message on the ATM, but attackers with the right access credentials can drain the ATM's cash vault and remove the malware from the system using an untraceable delete process.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The other types of malware usually behave in a similar fashion, capturing magnetic stripe data from the machine's memory storage and instructing the machines to withdraw cash.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attacks require a person with insider access, such as an ATM technician or anyone else with a key to the machine, to place the malware on the ATM.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The Tyupkin malware active in March 2014 on more than 50 ATMs at banking institutions in Eastern Europe, is believed to have also spread at the time to the U.S., India, and China.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The malware affects ATMs from major manufacturers running Microsoft Windows 32-bit operating systems.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The malware displays information on how much money is available in every machine and allows an attacker to withdraw 40 notes from the selected cassette of each ATM.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In June 2017, the financial software M.E.Doc, widely used in Ukraine, was identified by security researchers as a likely initial vector for the spread of the NotPetya malware.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Security researchers, including those from Microsoft, indicated that NotPetya infections may have originated from a compromised update issued through M.E.Doc.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Some analysts described this as a supply chain attack, though the exact method of compromise was not definitively identified.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The software's developers denied the claim but later deleted their statement and stated that they were cooperating with investigators.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] NotPetya was initially identified as ransomware because it encrypted hard drives and displayed a ransom demand in bitcoin.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] However, the email account used to provide decryption keys was shut down, leaving victims without a way to recover their files.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Unlike WannaCry, NotPetya had no built-in kill switch, making it harder to stop.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attack affected multiple industries in Ukraine, including banks, an airport, the Kyiv Metro, pharmaceutical companies, and Chernobyl's radiation detection systems.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] It also spread globally, impacting organizations in Russia, the United Kingdom, India, and the United States.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] NotPetya spread using EternalBlue, a vulnerability originally developed by the U.S.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] National Security Agency (NSA) and later leaked.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] EternalBlue had previously been used in the WannaCry cyberattack in May 2017.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] This exploit enabled NotPetya to spread through the Windows Server Message Block (SMB) protocol.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The malware also used PsExec and the Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to spread within networks.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Due to these exploits, once a device on a network was infected, the malware could rapidly spread to other connected systems.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Ukrainian police stated that M.E.Doc employees could face criminal liability for negligence, citing repeated warnings from antivirus firms about security vulnerabilities in the company's cybersecurity infrastructure.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The head of Ukraine's CyberPolice, Colonel Serhiy Demydiuk, alleged that M.E.Doc had been repeatedly warned by security firms about weaknesses in its systems but failed to act, stating, "They knew about it." Authorities later reported that M.E.Doc cooperated with investigators.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] From August 21 until September 5, 2018 British Airways was under attack.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The British Airways website payment section contained a code that harvested customer payment data.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The injected code was written specifically to route credit card information to a domain baways.com, which could erroneously be thought to belong to British Airways.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Magecart is the entity believed to be behind the attack.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Magecart is a name attributed to multiple hacker groups that use skimming practices in order to steal customer information through online payment processes.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Approximately 380,000 customers had their personal and financial data compromised as a result of the attack.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] British Airways later reported in October, 2018 that an additional 185,000 customers may have had their personal information stolen as well.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The 2020 SolarWinds cyberattack was linked to a supply chain compromise targeting the IT infrastructure company SolarWinds, which provided software used by multiple U.S. federal institutions, including networks within the National Nuclear Security Administration (NNSA).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Russian hackers compromised Orion, a widely used network management software developed by SolarWinds, by injecting malicious code into software updates.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] This allowed them to gain unauthorized access to numerous organizations, including multiple U.S. government agencies that relied on Orion for IT monitoring and management.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Department of Homeland Security issued Emergency Directive 21-01, "*Mitigate SolarWinds Orion Code Compromise",* requiring affected federal agencies to disconnect compromised Windows host OS instances from their enterprise domain and rebuild those hosts using trusted sources.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] These compromised systems had been running SolarWinds Orion.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In December 2020, FireEye identified a cyber breach involving the SolarWinds Orion software, which had been compromised prior to its discovery.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft was among the organizations affected, detecting and removing malicious files linked to the breach.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft has since collaborated with FireEye as part of an ongoing investigation into the incident.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The cyberattack targeted supply chain software used across various industries, including government, consulting, technology, telecommunications, and extractive sectors in North America, Europe, Asia and the Middle East.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] None of the Microsoft repositories contained production credentials.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The repositories were secured in December, and those attacks ceased in January.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] However, in March 2021 more than 20,000 US organizations were compromised through a back door that was installed via flaws in Exchange Server.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The affected organizations use self-hosted e-mail (on-site rather than cloud-based) such as credit unions, town governments, and small businesses.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The flaws were patched on 2 March 2021, but by 5 March 2021 only 10% of the compromised organizations had implemented the patch; the back door remains open.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The US officials are attempting to notify the affected organizations which are smaller than the organizations that were affected in December 2020.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Microsoft has updated its Indicators of Compromise tool and has released emergency mitigation measures for its Exchange Server flaws.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attacks on SolarWinds and Microsoft software are currently thought to be independent, as of March 2021.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The Indicators of Compromise tool allows customers to scan their Exchange Server log files for compromise.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] At least 10 attacking groups are using the Exchange Server flaws.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Web shells can remain on a patched server; this still allows cyberattacks based on the affected servers.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] As of 12 March 2021 exploit attempts are doubling every few hours, according to Check Point Research, some in the name of security researchers themselves.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] By 14 April 2021 the FBI had completed a covert cyber operation to remove the web shells from afflicted servers and was informing the servers' owners of what had been done.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In May 2021 Microsoft identified 3000 malicious emails to 150 organizations in 24 countries, that were launched by a group that Microsoft has denoted 'Nobelium'.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Many of those emails were blocked before delivery.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] 'Nobelium' gained access to a Constant Contact "email marketing account used by the US Agency for International Development (USAID)".
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Security researchers assert that 'Nobelium' crafts spear-phishing email messages which get clicked on by unsuspecting users; the links then direct installation of malicious 'Nobelium' code to infect the users' systems, making them subject to ransom, espionage, disinformation, etc.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The US government has identified 'Nobelium' as stemming from Russia's Federal Security Service.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] By July 2021 the US government is expected to name the initiator of the Exchange Server attacks: "China's Ministry of State Security has been using criminal contract hackers".
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In September 2021 the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) enforcement staff have requested that any companies which have downloaded any compromised SolarWinds updates, voluntarily turn over data to the SEC if they have installed the compromised updates on their servers.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In July 2022 SessionManager, a malicious module hosted by IIS (installed by default on Exchange Servers), was discovered to have infected Exchange Servers since March 2021; SessionManager searches memory for passwords, and downloads new modules, to hijack the server.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Mandiant, a security firm, has shown that nation-state-sponsored groups, once they have gained access to corporate clouds, can now exploit Security assertion markup language (SAML), to gain federated authentication to Active Directory and similar services, at will.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Once the attackers gain access, they are able to infiltrate any information or assets belonging to the organization.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] This is because this technique allows attackers to pose as any member of the targeted organization.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] These attacks are progressively becoming more desirable to malicious actors as companies and agencies continue to move assets to cloud services.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In 2020, SolarWinds was subject to what is described as the first documented Golden SAML attack, often referred to as "Solorigate".
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] A malicious actor infected the source code of a software update with a backdoor code made to look legitimate.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Customers began installing the faulty update to their systems, ultimately affecting over 18,000 individuals globally.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attack affected a number of United States government agencies and private sector agencies as well.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In May 2021, a ransomware attack on Colonial Pipeline forced a temporary shutdown of a major fuel distribution network, disrupting the supply of gasoline, diesel, and jet fuel to the U.S.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The Biden administration invoked emergency powers to prevent shortages, while experts described the incident as the worst-ever cyberattack on U.S. infrastructure.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attack, attributed to the Russian-linked cybercriminal group DarkSide, raised concerns about vulnerabilities in critical energy systems, as fuel traders sought alternative supply routes and fears of price spikes emerged.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] On June 16, 2021, President Biden stated to President Putin that cyberattacks on 16 critical infrastructure sectors were off-limits and said that the U.S. would respond to future cyber threats.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The 16 critical infrastructure sectors, as designated by the U.S.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA), include energy, food and agriculture, emergency services, healthcare, and other essential industries such as financial services, communications, and transportation systems.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] On 2 July 2021, about 60 managed service providers (MSPs) and their customers became victims of a ransomware attack perpetrated by the REvil group, causing downtime for over 1,000 companies.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] REvil carried out the attack by exploiting a vulnerability in VSA (Virtual System Administrator), a remote monitoring and management software package developed by Kaseya.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] This was a form of supply chain attack on a software supply chain.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] REvil demanded about 70 million USD in Bitcoin as a ransom.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] On 23 July 2021, Kaseya announced that it had received a universal decryptor tool from a "trusted third party", and it helped customers restore their data.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Two suspects were identified and one sentenced.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In March 2023, the voice and video chat app 3CX Phone System was thought to have been subject to a supply chain attack due to detection of malicious activity on the software.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The app is used in a wide variety of industries from food to automotive and an attack has the potential to impact hundreds of thousands of users worldwide.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The malware infects the host device through the installation process, acting as a Trojan horse virus spread through both Mac OS and Microsoft installers.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] They employed an infostealer through a malicious payload that connected to a C2 server controlled by the threat actor.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attack utilized the Gopuram backdoor, originally discovered by the Russian cybersecurity company Kaspersky in 2020.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The use of this backdoor suggested that the attack was executed by the North Korean cybercrime group known as Lazarus due to their use of this same backdoor in a 2020 attack against a South Asian cryptocurrency company.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The Gopuram backdoor has been utilized in other past attacks against cryptocurrency agencies, which Lazarus has been known to target.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In July 2023, Chinese state-sponsored hackers targeted the United States Department of State, hacking several government employees' Microsoft email accounts, which gave them access to classified information.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] They stole information from about 60,000 emails from several Department of State employees.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Department of State officials have stated that the information stolen includes "victims' travel itineraries and diplomatic deliberations".
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] If used in a malicious manner, this information could be used to monitor important government officials and track United States communications that are meant to be confidential.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The Department of State hack occurred due to vulnerabilities in Microsoft Exchange Server, classifying it as a supply-chain attack.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In March 2024, a backdoor in xz/liblzma in XZ Utils was suspected, with malicious code known to be in version 5.6.0 and 5.6.1.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] While the exploit remained dormant unless a specific third-party patch of the SSH server is used, under the right circumstances this interference could potentially enable a malicious actor to break sshd authentication and gain unauthorized access to the entire system remotely.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The list of affected Linux distributions includes Debian unstable, Fedora Rawhide, Kali Linux, and OpenSUSE Tumbleweed.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Most Linux distributions that followed a stable release update model were not affected, since they were carrying older versions of xz.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Arch Linux issued an advisory for users to update immediately, although it also noted that Arch's OpenSSH package does not include the common third-party patch necessary for the backdoor.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] FreeBSD is not affected by this attack, as all supported FreeBSD releases include versions of xz that predate the affected releases and the attack targets Linux's glibc.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] On October 31, 2024, cybersecurity researchers from several security firms such as Phylum, Socket, and Checkmarx detected an attack on users of the open-source Node Package Manager (NPM) library.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Unidentified attackers published more than 287 packages in an attempt to trick users of the platform into downloading malicious code.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attack used a technique called typosquatting, which copies the names of legitimate packages closely, tricking unsuspecting developers into accidentally downloading the wrong one.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] For the package Fetch-mock-jest, the attacker rearranged the order of the words and misspelled the word fetch creating the name "jest-fet-mock".
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Based on the kind of packages mimicked, researchers believe this attack widely targeted software developers using NPM.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Packages targeted are mostly mock HTTP requests and cryptocurrency-related, including Puppeteer, Bignum.js, and Fetch-mock-jest, which are mainly used in development environments.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Phylum researchers noted that these typosquatted packages seemed normal at first glance, but upon closer inspection, they contained obfuscated code that could not be understood.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] After de-obfuscating the code, researchers found that after the malicious package is mistakenly downloaded it automatically runs a script that interacts with an Ethereum smart contract to retrieve the IP addresses of the command and control server (C2) used by the attackers.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The script then identifies the operating system used by the victim machine and downloads compatible malware from the IP address it received from the contract.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] This malware maintains persistent communication with the attacker's C2 server, periodically leaking the user's system information such as the operating system version, GPU, CPU, the amount of memory on the machine, and username.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Checkmarkx researcher Yahud Gelb explains that if researchers attempt to take down a C2 server at a specific IP address, the attacker can just update the Ethereum contract so that it returns a different address.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] When describing the mechanism behind the contract he wrote: "Think of a smart contract on the Ethereum blockchain as a public bulletin board – anyone can read what's posted, but only the owner has the ability to update it".
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] This complicates the issue because the malware can always query the smart contract to update the stored address of the C2 server in case the current one has been taken down by authorities.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Researchers worried that several companies' software development supply chains can be put at risk when attackers typosquat them.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] They elaborate that the untraceable nature of the attack combined with its precisely engineered methods of persistence only adds to the looming threat.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Furthermore, company employees usually have elevated system privileges and access to CI/CD pipelines when using development environments, further endangering the company's and their customer's data.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] They warned that developers who use npm packages like the ones above at any stage of the software development lifecycle must take caution and implement robust dependency scanning before performing any installations.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] There is little to no information on the attackers' identity or their motive.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] However, researchers did find error messages written in Russian within the de-obfuscated code of the malicious packages, but they speculate that this could be a misdirect set up by the real culprits trying to throw off any suspicions.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In 2025, the popular text editor Notepad++ was subjected to a sophisticated supply chain attack when threat actors compromised the application's update infrastructure at the hosting provider level.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attack, which began in June 2025 and continued through December 2025, involved the interception and redirection of update traffic from the official notepad-plus-plus.org domain to attacker-controlled servers.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] According to the Notepad++ maintainer, the shared hosting server was fully compromised until September 2, 2025, after which attackers maintained access to internal service credentials until December 2, 2025, allowing them to continue redirecting update traffic.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Kaspersky researchers identified three primary execution chains used between July and October 2025, with attackers constantly changing command-and-control server addresses, downloaders, and final payloads to evade detection.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Security firm Rapid7 attributed the campaign to the Lotus Blossom group (also known as Violet Typhoon or APT31), linking the attacks to infrastructure and tactics previously observed in campaigns targeting cryptocurrency companies and critical infrastructure.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] On January 20, 2026, the eScan antivirus software, developed by Indian cybersecurity firm MicroWorld Technologies, was compromised in a supply chain attack when threat actors breached one of the company's regional update servers and deployed malware to customer systems.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The incident lasted approximately one hour before being detected by security researchers at Morphisec and Kaspersky.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The attack primarily affected users in South Asia, including India, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, and the Philippines.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Attackers replaced the legitimate Reload.exe component of eScan with a malicious executable that disabled future antivirus updates and downloaded additional payloads from command-and-control servers.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] This marked the second breach of eScan's infrastructure, following a 2024 incident where North Korean state-sponsored group Kimsuky exploited the same update mechanism to deploy backdoors and cryptocurrency miners.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] No attribution has been made for the 2026 attack.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] On 12 May 2021, Executive Order 14028 (the EO), *Improving the nation's cybersecurity*, tasked NIST as well as other US government agencies with enhancing the cybersecurity of the United States.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The Comprehensive National Cybersecurity Initiative and the Cyberspace Policy Review passed by the Bush and Obama administrations respectively, direct U.S. federal funding for development of multi-pronged approaches for global supply chain risk management.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] According to Adrian Davis of the Technology Innovation Management Review, securing organizations from supply chain attacks begins with building cyber-resilient systems.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain resilience is, according to supply chain risk management expert Donal Walters, "the ability of the supply chain to cope with unexpected disturbances" and one of its characteristics is a company-wide recognition of where the supply chain is most susceptible to infiltration.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain management plays a crucial role in creating effective supply chain resilience.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In March 2015, under the Conservative and Liberal democratic government coalition, the UK Department for Business outlined new efforts to protect SMEs from cyber attacks, which included measures to improve supply chain resilience.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The UK government has produced the Cyber Essentials Scheme, which trains firms for good practices to protect their supply chain and overall cyber security.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] In 2025, a study by the Austrian Chamber of Commerce (WKO) and AV-Comparatives identified what cybersecurity firms should do to assure their customers about supply chain security.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] This includes disclosing a software bill of materials, maintaining transparent data storage practices, providing detailed incident reports, and offering facilities where customers can inspect source codes and updates for the cybersecurity product.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Only 3 of the 14 vendors examined provided such assurances.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] Supply chain attacks have prompted regulatory bodies to address third-party risk management requirements.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] The Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA) issued Binding Operational Directive 22-01, requiring federal agencies to remediate known exploited vulnerabilities within specified timeframes.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/supply-chain-attack] NIST Special Publication 800-161 *Cybersecurity Supply Chain Risk Management Practices* provides a framework for organizations to identify, assess, and mitigate supply chain risks throughout the system development life cycle.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Once on the typosquatter's site, the user may also be tricked into thinking that they are actually on the real site through the use of copied or similar logos, website layouts, or content.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Spam emails sometimes make use of typosquatting URLs to trick users into visiting malicious sites that look like a given bank's site, for instance.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Many companies, including Verizon, Lufthansa, and Lego, have gained reputations for aggressively chasing down typosquatted names.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Lego, for example, has spent roughly US$500,000 on taking 309 cases through UDRP proceedings.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Celebrities have also pursued their domain names.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Prominent examples include basketball player Dirk Nowitzki's UDRP of DirkSwish.com and actress Eva Longoria's UDRP of EvaLongoria.org.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Later, the URL was redirected to google.com; a 2018 check revealed it to redirect users to adware pages, and a 2020 attempt to access the site through a private DNS resolver hosted by AdGuard resulted in the page being identified as malware and blocked for the user's security.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] By mid-2022, it had been turned into a political blog.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] However, as of July 2026, goggle.com is no longer operational.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] In February 2026, researchers at Have I Been Squatted, working with Ctrl-Alt-Intel, reported a phishing operation called Diesel Vortex that targeted freight and logistics organizations in the United States and Europe.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] The campaign used lookalike domains and phishing pages impersonating logistics services, and was reported to have stolen more than 1,600 unique credentials from logistics platforms.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Another example of corporate typosquatting is yuube.com, targeting YouTube users by programming that URL to redirect to a malicious website or page that asks users to add a malware "security check extension".
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Similarly, www.airfrance.com has been typosquatted by www.arifrance.com, diverting users to a website peddling discount travel (although it now redirects to a warning from Air France about malware).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Other examples are equifacks.com (Equifax.com), experianne.com (Experian.com), and tramsonion.com (TransUnion.com); these three typosquatted sites were registered by comedian John Oliver for his show *Last Week Tonight*.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Over 550 typosquats related to the 2020 U.S. presidential election were detected in 2019.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] The Magniber ransomware is being distributed in a typosquatting method that exploits typos made when entering domains, targeting mainly Chrome and Edge users.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] A 2024 peer-reviewed study provides the first large-scale measurement of typosquatting in blockchain-based naming systems, such as Ethereum Name Service, Unstoppable Domains, and ADAHandles.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] The researchers observed thousands of cryptocurrency transactions mistakenly sent to squatting addresses, with targets including both popular domain names and identities linked to social media accounts.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] In the United States, the 1999 Anticybersquatting Consumer Protection Act (ACPA) contains a clause (Section 3(a), amending 15 USC 1117 to include sub-section (d)(2)(B)(ii)) aimed at combatting typosquatting.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] On April 17, 2006, evangelist Jerry Falwell failed to get the U.S Supreme Court to review a decision allowing Christopher Lamparello to use www.fallwell.com.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Relying on a plausible misspelling of Falwell's name, Lamparello's gripe site presents misdirected visitors with scriptural references that are intended to counter the fundamentalist preacher's scathing rebukes against homosexuality.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] Under the Uniform Domain-Name Dispute-Resolution Policy (UDRP), trademark holders can file a case at the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) against typosquatters (as with cybersquatters in general).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/typosquatting] The complainant has to show that the registered domain name is identical or confusingly similar to their trademark, that the registrant has no legitimate interest in the domain name, and that the domain name is being used in bad faith.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The objective of the cheat sheet is to provide a proposal of approach regarding the handling of vulnerable third-party dependencies when they are detected, and this, depending on different situation.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Proposals mentioned in this cheat sheet are not silver-bullet (recipes that work in all situations) yet can be used as a foundation and adapted to your context.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Most of the projects use third-party dependencies to delegate handling of different kind of operations, *e.g.* generation of document in a specific format, HTTP communications, data parsing of a specific format, etc.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's a good approach because it allows the development team to focus on the real application code supporting the expected business feature.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The dependency brings forth an expected downside where the security posture of the real application is now resting on it.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's highly recommended to perform automated analysis of the dependencies from the birth of the project.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Indeed, if this task is added at the middle or end of the project, it can imply a huge amount of work to handle all the issues identified and that will in turn impose a huge burden on the development team and might to blocking the advancement of the project at hand.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In the rest of the cheat sheet, when we refer to *development team* then we assume that the team contains a member with the required application security skills or can refer to someone in the company having these kind of skills to analyse the vulnerability impacting the dependency.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] It's important to keep in mind the different ways in which a security issue is handled after its discovery.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Here, the vulnerability is always referenced in the CVE global database used, generally, by the detection tools as one of the several input sources used.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] See a description here, into the section named **Computers** about **Computer Security**.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The researcher decides to release all the information including exploitation code/method on services like Full Disclosure mailing list, Exploit-DB.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Here a CVE is not always created then the vulnerability is not always in the CVE global database causing the detection tools to be potentially blind about unless the tools use other input sources.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] When a security issue is detected, it's possible to decide to accept the risk represented by the security issue.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] However, this decision must be taken by the Chief Risk Officer (fallback possible to Chief Information Security Officer) of the company based on technical feedback from the development team that have analyzed the issue (see the *Cases* section) as well as the CVEs CVSS score indicators.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] When a security issue is detected, the development team can meet one of the situations (named *Case* in the rest of the cheat sheet) presented in the sub sections below.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the vulnerably impact a transitive dependency then the action will be taken on the direct dependency of the project because acting on a transitive dependency often impact the stability of the application.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Acting on a on a transitive dependency require the development team to fully understand the complete relation/communication/usage from the project first level dependency until the dependency impacted by the security vulnerability, this task is very time consuming.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Patched version of the component has been released by the provider.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests exist for the features of the application using the impacted dependency allowing to validate that the feature is operational.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Update the version of the dependency in the project on a testing environment.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider informs the team that it will take a while to fix the issue and, so, a patched version will not be available before months.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If a workaround is provided, it should be applied and validated on the testing environment, and thereafter deployed to production.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has given the team a list of the impacted functions, protective code must wrap the calls to these functions to ensure that the input and the output data is safe.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Moreover, security devices, such as the Web Application Firewall (WAF), can handle such issues by protecting the internal applications through parameter validation and by generating detection rules for those specific libraries.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Yet, in this cheat sheet, the focus is set on the application level in order to patch the vulnerability as close as possible to the source.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has provided nothing about the vulnerability, Case 3 can be applied skipping the *step 2* of this case.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] We assume here that, at least, the CVE has been provided.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If the provider has provided the team with the exploitation code, and the team made a security wrapper around the vulnerable library/code, execute the exploitation code in order to ensure that the library is now secure and doesn't affect the application.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If you have a set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests that exist for the application, run them to verify that the protection code added does not impact the stability of the application.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Add a comment in the project *README* explaining that the issue (specify the related CVE) is handled during the waiting time of a patched version because the detection tool will continue to raise an alert on this dependency.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider informs the team that they cannot fix the issue, so no patched version will be released at all (applies also if provider does not want to fix the issue or does not answer at all).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In this case the only information given to the development team is the CVE.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Nothing specific because here we are in a *patch yourself* condition.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] In all cases, here, we need to handle the vulnerability right now.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] As we know the vulnerable dependency, we know where it is used in the application (if it's a transitive dependency then we can identify the first level dependency using it using the IDE built-in feature or the dependency management system used (Maven, Gradle, NuGet, npm, etc.).
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Note that IDE is also used to identify the calls to the dependency.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Identifying calls to this dependency is fine but it is the first step.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The team still lacks information on what kind of patching needs to be performed.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] To obtain these information, the team uses the CVE content to know which kind of vulnerability affects the dependency.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The `description` property provides the answer: SQL injection, Remote Code Execution, Cross-Site Scripting, Cross-Site Request Forgery, etc.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] After identifying the above 2 points, the team is aware of the type of patching that needs to be taken (Case 2 with the protective code) and where to add it.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] The team has an application using the Jackson API in a version exposed to the CVE-2016-3720.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Based on these information, the team determines that the necessary patching will be to add a pre-validation of any XML data passed to the Jakson API to prevent XML external entity (XXE) vulnerability.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If possible, create a unit test that mimics the vulnerability in order to ensure that the patch is effective and have a way to continuously ensure that the patch is in place during the evolution of the project.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] If you have a set of automated unit or integration or functional or security tests that exists for the application then run them to verify that the patch does not impact the stability of the application.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Provider collaborates with you after being notified of the vulnerability.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] Inform the provider about the vulnerability by sharing the post with them.
[src:software-supply-chain-security/vulnerable-dependency-management-cheat-sheet] This section lists several tools that can used to analyze the dependencies used by a project in order to detect the vulnerabilities.
